solution: ```class Solution {
    public int findKthNumber(int n, int k) {
        int curr = 1;
        k--;
        while (k > 0) {
            long step = 0, first = curr, last = curr + 1;
            while (first <= n) {
                step += Math.min((long) n + 1, last) - first;
                first *= 10;
                last *= 10;
            }
            if (step <= k) {
                curr++;
                k -= step;
            } else {
                curr *= 10;
                k--;
            }
        }
        return curr;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log n * log n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a digit-tree counting approach: treat numbers as nodes in a 10-ary tree and count how many numbers fall under each prefix without generating them. Moves either to the next sibling or dives into the first child, adjusting k accordingly. Avoids full enumeration, handling the 1e9 bound efficiently.

